1\. Here’s a comparison table between Basic Kanban, Automated Kanban, and Bug Triage:

| Aspect | Basic Kanban | Automated Kanban | Bug Triage |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Definition | A visual system for managing work, focusing on flow. | A Kanban system where tasks are managed with automated tools or triggers. | The process of sorting, prioritizing, and assigning bugs or issues. |
| Workflows | Tasks are moved manually across boards/stages (e.g., To Do, In Progress, Done). | Tasks are moved based on set rules or triggers (e.g., automatically assigned, moved between columns based on status). | Bugs are categorized, prioritized, and assigned based on severity, impact, and other criteria. |
| Automation | No automation; tasks are manually updated. | High level of automation (e.g., task creation, assignment, status updates). | Some automation can be used for triaging bugs but primarily a manual process. |
| Key Focus | Work management, limiting work in progress (WIP), and improving flow. | Efficiency through automation of task flow. | Identifying and prioritizing critical bugs. |
| Tools/Software | Kanban boards (physical or digital like Trello, Jira). | Kanban tools with automation features (e.g., Jira, Monday.com, Trello with Power-Ups). | Bug tracking tools (e.g., Jira, Bugzilla, Redmine). |
| Benefits | Simple, flexible, and visual system for managing tasks. | Reduces manual effort, increases efficiency, and minimizes human error. | Helps identify and resolve the most critical issues quickly. |
| Typical Use Case | Software development, project management, general workflow management. | Projects with high volume or repetitive tasks, or teams that need frequent updates/assignments. | Software development or IT operations dealing with issues and bugs. |
| Complexity | Simple to implement and manage. | Requires setup of automation rules and integration with tools. | Involves setting up prioritization criteria, such as severity, impact, and reproducibility. |
| Team Involvement | Low team involvement; each member updates the board as needed. | Medium to high; automation needs setup but fewer manual updates once in place. | High team involvement, especially for prioritization and fixing. |
| Scalability | Scalable for smaller teams and simple processes. | Scalable for larger teams and more complex workflows. | Scalable for teams with large volumes of bugs or frequent releases. |
| Adaptability | Can be adapted to any type of workflow or project. | Adaptable but depends on the tools' capabilities. | Adaptable to various bug tracking needs, but usually specific to software development. |

3\. Kanban Board Explanation:

A Kanban board is essentially a visual representation of the tasks in the project. It consists of columns that represent different stages of the work process (e.g., Backlog, In Progress, Testing, Done). Each task is represented by a card that moves across the columns as the task progresses.

A Kanban board can be a very powerful tool to manage the workflow of a boat rental system project. It not only helps visualize the workflow but also supports Agile principles by promoting continuous delivery, flexibility, and transparency.

Kanban provides a clear, visual way of managing these components. With columns representing stages of work, team members can see at a glance the status of various tasks. This transparency makes it easier for everyone on the team to track progress and prioritize work.

It aligns with the iterative and evolving nature of software development by providing clear structure without introducing unnecessary complexity. Additionally, it helps small teams manage tasks effectively while providing transparency, limiting work in progress, and promoting continuous improvement, all of which are crucial as the boat rental system evolves and scales.

My Kanban board will set the WIP limit to 3 on the "In Progress" column, this means that only 3 tasks can be worked on at any time in that column. No one can start working on a new task until one of the existing tasks is completed and moved to the next stage.

WIP limits help prevent multitasking, which can lead to lower quality and incomplete tasks. When fewer tasks are in progress, there is a clearer focus on getting those tasks done. Limiting WIP often leads to faster throughput because teams are forced to move tasks along the workflow and prevent bottlenecks in any stage. Limiting the amount of work in progress can also reduce errors and allow for more thorough work, as there is less pressure to juggle multiple tasks at once.

My basic Kanban board supports Agile principles by offering transparency, continuous flow, and a framework for flexibility, prioritization, and iterative improvement. It will help teams focus on delivering value incrementally, responding to change, and fostering collaboration. Through the use of visual management and WIP limits, my team can work more efficiently, improve communication, and continuously evolve their processes to better meet customer needs and project goals.

4\. Reflection:

Selecting and customizing a Kanban board template for your system can offer great benefits, but it also comes with several challenges. Balancing customization and functionality while Kanban boards are meant to be simple and intuitive, adding too many customizations can make the board too complex, which might reduce the effectiveness of the tool.

Deciding which columns to include in your Kanban board can also be tricky. You need to ensure the board matches the stages of your process, but it's easy to overcomplicate this step by adding too many columns. What I have learned as a result is to avoid having too many columns that don’t add significant value or that duplicate other stages. Keep the process simple and focused on key steps.

Setting appropriate WIP limits for each column is critical but can be hard to determine, especially if your team is new to Kanban or you're working in an unfamiliar domain. Too few tasks can cause underutilization, while too many tasks can lead to bottlenecks and delays. A possible solution to this is to involve the team in deciding WIP limits based on their experiences and workloads. Be prepared to adjust limits as you learn what works best.

Overall, the key challenges include ensuring that the board fits your team’s workflow, balancing simplicity with customization, setting the right WIP limits, ensuring easy integration with other tools, and encouraging team adoption. By carefully considering your team’s needs, starting with a simple template, and making iterative adjustments, you can create a Kanban board that boosts productivity and aligns with your system’s goals.
